Practical No. 10
Aim:
Predict whether a student will pass (1) or fail (0) based on number of study hours.
Theory:
Logistic Regression is a supervised machine learning algorithm used for classification problems
where the dependent variable has only two possible outcomes such as pass/fail, true/false, or 1/0.
Unlike linear regression, which predicts continuous values, logistic regression predicts the
probability of a class using a sigmoid function.
Steps:
1. Create Dataset
Define study hours and corresponding results.
hours <- c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8)
result <- c(0,0,0,0,1,1,1,1)
data <- data.frame(hours, result)
2. Apply Logistic Regression
model <- glm(result ~ hours, data = data, family = binomial)
3. Predict Probability
predicted_prob <- predict(model, type = "response")
print(predicted_prob)
4. Convert Probability to Class
predicted_class <- ifelse(predicted_prob > 0.5, 1, 0)
print(predicted_class)
5. Confusion Matrix
table(Predicted = predicted_class, Actual = data$result)
6. Plot Graph
plot(data$hours, data$result,
xlab = "Study hours",
ylab = "Pass (1) / Fail (0)",
main = "Logistic Regression")
7. Plot Logistic Curve
curve(predict(model, data.frame(hours = x), type = "response"),
add = TRUE, col = "blue")
Conclusion:
Logistic regression successfully predicts whether a student will pass or fail based on study hours. It
calculates probability and classifies outcomes, making it useful for binary classification problems.
